#### Generality of spacing effect

We have already seen that spaced repetition is effective on a variety of academic fields and mediums. Beyond that, spacing effects can be found in:

- various "domains (e.g., learning perceptual motor tasks or learning lists of words)"^[See [Cepeda et al 2006](http://uweb.cas.usf.edu/~drohrer/pdfs/Cepeda_et_al_2006PsychBull.pdf "Distributed Practice in Verbal Recall Tasks: A Review and Quantitative Synthesis")] such as spatial^[Commins, S., Cunningham, L., Harvey, D., and Walsh, D. (2003). ["Massed but not spaced training impairs spatial memory"](/docs/spacedrepetition/2003-commins.pdf). _Behavioural Brain Research_ 139, 215-223]
- "across species (e.g., [rats](http://www.jneurosci.org/content/21/7/2404.long "'Long-term memory is facilitated by cAMP response element-binding protein overexpression in the amygdala', Josselyn et al 2001"), pigeons, and humans [or [flies](http://dubnaulab.cshl.edu/pdf/margulies2005.pdf "'Deconstructing Memory in Drosophila', Margulies et al 2005") or [bumblebees](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC311375/ "'Massed and Spaced Learning in Honeybees: The Role of CS, US, the Intertrial Interval, and the Test Interval', Menzel et al 2001"), and sea slugs, [Carew et al 1972](/docs/spacedrepetition/1972-carew.pdf "'Long-Term Habituation of a Defensive Withdrawal Reflex in Aplysia', Carew et al 1972") & [Sutton et al 2002](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC155928/)])"
